You're working on a project to develop a weather application that provides weather
updates to users. You decided to integrate with a third-party weather API to fetch
weather data. However, the API uses a different interface format compared to what your
application expects.
Using the Adapter design pattern (class adapter) , design a solution to seamlessly
integrate the third-party weather API with your weather application. Consider the
following details:

a. The third-party weather API uses a non-standard interface format.
class ThirdPartyWeatherAPI {
double fetchTemperature() { }
double fetchHumidity() { }
double fetchWindSpeed() { }
double fetchPrecipitation() { }
}
b. Your weather application expects a unified interface for retrieving weather
information, with methods such as getTemperature(), getHumidity(),
getWindSpeed(), and getPrecipitation().
c. The adapter should translate calls from the standard interface of your
weather application to the specific interface of the third-party API, enabling
smooth integration between the two systems.

Here is the implementation of the Adapter design pattern (class adapter) for integrating the third-party weather API with the weather application:

```java
// Standard interface expected by the weather application
interface WeatherAdapter {
    double getTemperature();
    double getHumidity();
    double getWindSpeed();
    double getPrecipitation();
}

// Third-party weather API with non-standard interface format
class ThirdPartyWeatherAPI {
    double fetchTemperature() {
        // Fetch temperature from third-party API
    }

    double fetchHumidity() {
        // Fetch humidity from third-party API
    }

    double fetchWindSpeed() {
        // Fetch wind speed from third-party API
    }

    double fetchPrecipitation() {
        // Fetch precipitation from third-party API
    }
}

// Adapter class to integrate the third-party weather API with the weather application
class WeatherAPIAdapter extends ThirdPartyWeatherAPI implements WeatherAdapter {
    @Override
    public double getTemperature() {
        return fetchTemperature();
    }

    @Override
    public double getHumidity() {
        return fetchHumidity();
    }

    @Override
    public double getWindSpeed() {
        return fetchWindSpeed();
    }

    @Override
    public double getPrecipitation() {
        return fetchPrecipitation();
    }
}

// Weather application
class WeatherApplication {
    private WeatherAdapter weatherAdapter;

    public WeatherApplication(WeatherAdapter weatherAdapter) {
        this.weatherAdapter = weatherAdapter;
    }

    public void displayWeatherData() {
        System.out.println("Temperature: " + weatherAdapter.getTemperature());
        System.out.println("Humidity: " + weatherAdapter.getHumidity());
        System.out.println("Wind Speed: " + weatherAdapter.getWindSpeed());
        System.out.println("Precipitation: " + weatherAdapter.getPrecipitation());
    }
}

// Main class for testing the adapter
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ThirdPartyWeatherAPI thirdPartyAPI = new ThirdPartyWeatherAPI();
        WeatherAdapter adapter = new WeatherAPIAdapter();
        WeatherApplication weatherApp = new WeatherApplication(adapter);

        // Display weather data using the adapter
        weatherApp.displayWeatherData();
    }
}
```

In this implementation:
- The `WeatherAdapter` interface defines the standard methods expected by the weather application.
- The `ThirdPartyWeatherAPI` class provides weather data through non-standard methods.
- The `WeatherAPIAdapter` class adapts calls from the standard interface of the weather application to the specific interface of the third-party API.
- The `WeatherApplication` class uses the `WeatherAdapter` to display weather data seamlessly.

